        "ticket_id": "INC-5001",
        "subject": "Outlook keeps crashing when I open large emails",
        "description": "Hi IT support,\n\nI need help with Outlook. It crashes consistently when I try to open certain emails, particularly ones with large inline content. I've tried everything I can think of — cleared the cache, repaired the Office installation, even reinstalled it completely. Nothing helps.\n\nLet me give you some background. I'm in the Wealth Management team and we receive a lot of client correspondence with embedded charts, tables, and sometimes inline images. The problem started about a week ago after the March Windows update. Before that, everything was fine.\n\nHere's what happens step by step:\n1. I open Outlook normally — it loads fine\n2. I navigate to my inbox — works fine\n3. I click on an email from our client reporting system — the preview pane shows the email header but then Outlook freezes\n4. After about 10-15 seconds, I get the 'Not Responding' message\n5. Then Outlook crashes with an error dialog that says 'Microsoft Outlook has stopped working'\n6. Sometimes it offers to restart in safe mode, which I've tried, but the same emails still crash it\n\nI've noticed the problematic emails all seem to be the automated reports from our portfolio management system. These emails typically contain:\n- 15-20 inline charts as embedded images\n- Large HTML tables with 500+ rows of position data\n- Multiple embedded Excel snippets\n- The total email size is usually 8-12 MB\n\nI tried forwarding one of these emails to my personal account and opening it in the web browser version of Outlook — it works there, just very slowly. So the data in the email seems fine, it's the desktop client that can't handle it.\n\nOther things I've tried:\n- Running Outlook in safe mode (still crashes on these specific emails)\n- Creating a new Outlook profile (same issue)\n- Disabling all COM add-ins (still crashes)\n- Running the Office repair tool (both quick and online repair)\n- Checking for Office updates (I'm on the latest version: Microsoft 365 Apps, Version 2403, Build 17425.20228)\n- Increasing the Outlook cache size in the registry\n- Clearing the Outlook temp folders\n- Running SFC /scannow (found no issues)\n- Checking Event Viewer — I see application error events for OUTLOOK.EXE with exception code 0xc0000005 (access violation)\n\nMy system specs:\n- Dell Latitude 7440, 16GB RAM, Intel i7-1365U\n- Windows 11 Enterprise 23H2\n- 256GB SSD with 89GB free\n- Connected via Ethernet in the NYC office, Floor 3\n\nThis is really impacting my work because these automated reports are how I track client portfolio performance. I'm currently having to use the web version of Outlook which is much slower and doesn't integrate with our other desktop tools.\n\nI've attached the Event Viewer export showing the crash events. Please let me know if you need any other information.\n\nThanks for your help,\nMelissa\n\nP.S. — My colleague Janet mentioned she had a similar issue last month but hers resolved after an update. Not sure if that helps.\n\nP.P.S. — I also noticed that my Outlook search hasn't been working properly since the crashes started. It shows results from months ago but not recent emails. Might be related to the indexing service getting corrupted by the crashes?\n\n---\nMelissa Chang\nSenior Portfolio Manager | Wealth Management\nContoso Financial Services\nOne Financial Plaza, Floor 3\nNew York, NY 10004\nTel: +1 (212) 555-0147\nEmail: melissa.chang@contoso.com\n\nCONFIDENTIALITY NOTICE: This email and any attachments are for the exclusive and confidential use of the intended recipient. If you are not the intended recipient, please do not read, distribute, or take action based on this message. If you have received this in error, please notify the sender immediately by return email and delete this message from your system. Contoso Financial Services does not accept liability for any damage caused by any virus transmitted by this email.",
